  <h1 class="title">How to Stop Panic Attacks</h1>
  <p class="subtitle">A Professional, Evidence-Based Guide</p>

  <p>Panic attacks are acute episodes of intense fear accompanied by strong physiological reactions. While often perceived as dangerous, they are a misfiring of the body's threat detection system rather than a true medical emergency.</p>

  <h2>Understanding the Panic Cycle</h2>
  <p>Panic is sustained by a feedback loop between body and cognition:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Initial physical trigger (elevated heart rate)</li>
    <li>Catastrophic interpretation (“Something is wrong”)</li>
    <li>Adrenaline surge</li>
    <li>Escalation of symptoms</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Intervention requires disrupting this loop at both the physiological and cognitive levels.</p>

  <h2>Immediate Techniques</h2>

  <div class="box">
    <strong>Controlled Breathing</strong>
    <p>Use slow nasal inhalation (4 seconds) and extended exhalation (6 seconds) to regulate carbon dioxide levels and stabilize the nervous system.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="box">
    <strong>5-4-3-2-1 Grounding</strong>
    <p>Shift attention outward using sensory awareness to interrupt internal threat processing.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="box">
    <strong>Cold Exposure</strong>
    <p>Applying cold water or a cold object activates parasympathetic response and reduces heart rate.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="box">
    <strong>Cognitive Reframing</strong>
    <p>Replace catastrophic thoughts with accurate interpretations: “This is anxiety, not danger.”</p>
  </div>

  <h2>Long-Term Treatment</h2>
  <p>Cognitive Behavioral Therapy (CBT) is the most validated treatment model, focusing on:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Cognitive restructuring</li>
    <li>Exposure to feared sensations</li>
    <li>Behavioral adaptation</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Clinical outcomes show sustained improvement in a majority of patients when protocols are followed consistently.</p>

  <h2>Lifestyle Factors</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Reduce caffeine and stimulants</li>
    <li>Maintain consistent sleep patterns</li>
    <li>Engage in regular aerobic activity</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="highlight">
    “Panic persists not because it is dangerous, but because it is feared.”
  </div>

  <h2>When to Seek Professional Help</h2>
  <p>Consult a healthcare professional if panic begins to interfere with daily functioning, avoidance behaviors increase, or symptoms intensify over time.</p>

